6 PRETRIAL RELEASE
7
8 SECTION 1. ORS 135.233 is amended to read:
9 135.233. (1) The presiding judge of a judicial district shall enter a standing pretrial release order
10 specifying to the sheriff of the county, or to the entity supervising the local correctional facility
11 responsible for pretrial incarceration within the judicial district, those persons and offenses:
12 (a) Subject to release on recognizance;
NOTE: Matter in boldfaced type in an amended section is new; matter [italic and bracketed] is existing law to be omitted.
New sections are in boldfaced type.
LC 106

A-Eng. SB 1516
1 (b) Subject to release with special conditions as specified in the order; and
2 (c) That are not eligible for release until arraignment.
3 (2) The Chief Justice of the Supreme Court, with input from a criminal justice advisory com-
4 mittee appointed by the Chief Justice, shall establish release guidelines for the pretrial release or-
5 ders described in this section to:
6 (a) Provide consistent release decision-making structure across the state;
7 (b) Reduce reliance on the use of security;
8 (c) Include provisions for victim notification and input; and
9 (d) Balance the rights of the defendant and presumption of pretrial release against community
10 and victim safety and the risk of failure to appear.
11 (3) Any standing pretrial release order entered under subsection (1) of this section does
12 not affect the authority of a magistrate to make a release decision under ORS 135.245 and
13 to consider, when making the release decision, the primary and secondary release criteria,
14 including community safety and the risk of failure to appear by the defendant.
15 SECTION 2. ORS 135.230 is amended to read:
16 135.230. As used in ORS 135.230 to 135.290, unless the context requires otherwise:
17 (1) “Abuse” means:
18 (a) Attempting to cause or intentionally, knowingly or recklessly causing physical injury;
19 (b) Intentionally, knowingly or recklessly placing another in fear of imminent serious physical
20 injury; or
21 (c) Committing sexual abuse in any degree as defined in ORS 163.415, 163.425 and 163.427.
22 (2) “Conditional release” means a nonsecurity release which imposes regulations on the activ-
23 ities and associations of the defendant.
24 (3) “Domestic violence” means abuse between family or household members.
25 (4) “Family or household members” means any of the following:
26 (a) Spouses.
27 (b) Former spouses.
28 (c) Adult persons related by blood or marriage.
29 (d) Persons cohabiting with each other.
30 (e) Persons who have cohabited with each other or who have been involved in a sexually inti-
31 mate relationship.
32 (f) Unmarried parents of a minor child.
33 (5) “Magistrate” has the meaning provided for this term in ORS 133.030.
34 (6) “Personal recognizance” means the release of a defendant upon the promise of the defendant
35 to appear in court at all appropriate times.
36 (7) “Primary release criteria” includes the following:
37 (a) The reasonable protection of the victim or public;
38 (b) The nature of the current charge;
39 (c) The defendant’s prior criminal record, if any, and, if the defendant previously has been re-
40 leased pending trial, whether the defendant appeared as required;
41 (d) Any facts indicating the possibility of violations of law if the defendant is released without
42 regulations; and
43 (e) Any other facts tending to indicate [that] whether the defendant is likely to appear as re-
44 quired.
45 (8) “Release” means temporary or partial freedom of a defendant from lawful custody before
