20 AUTOMATED LICENSE PLATE RECOGNITION SYSTEMS
21
22 SECTION 3. Definitions. As used in sections 3 to 9 of this 2026 Act:
23 (1) “Alert” means a notification generated by an automated license plate recognition
24 system indicating that a vehicle’s license plate number or other vehicle characteristics
25 match information contained in a hot list or database described in section 4 of this 2026 Act.
26 (2) “Authorized user” means a law enforcement officer or other employee of a law
27 enforcement agency who is authorized to deploy or use an automated license plate recogni-
28 tion system or captured license plate data in accordance with the provisions of sections 3 to
29 9 of this 2026 Act.
30 (3)(a) “Automated license plate recognition system” means one or more high-speed cam-
31 eras combined with computer algorithms used to convert images of license plates or other
32 vehicle characteristics into computer-readable data.
33 (b) “Automated license plate recognition system” does not include a photo red light
34 camera described in ORS 810.434 when used for enforcement of ORS 811.265 or a photo radar
35 unit when used for enforcement of ORS 811.111.
36 (4) “Captured license plate data” means the global positioning system coordinates, date
37 and time, video, photograph, license plate number, vehicle characteristics or any other re-
38 lated data or information collected by an automated license plate recognition system.
39 (5) “Hot list” means a database created or maintained by a law enforcement agency that
40 identifies vehicles used to facilitate the commission of a crime or violation or to avoid ap-
41 prehension for commission of a crime, or that are associated with a missing or endangered
42 person.
43 (6) “Law enforcement agency” has the meaning given that term in ORS 181A.775.
44 (7) “Law enforcement purpose” means an authorized use of an automated license plate
45 recognition system or captured license plate data under section 4 of this 2026 Act.
[3]

A-Eng. SB 1516
1 (8) “Secured area” means an area, enclosed by clear boundaries, to which access is lim-
2 ited or not open to the public and entry is obtainable only through specific access control
3 points.
4 SECTION 4. Authorized uses of ALPR systems by law enforcement; requirements for use.
5 (1) Except as provided under sections 3 to 9 of this 2026 Act, a law enforcement agency may
6 not use an automated license plate recognition system or captured license plate data.
7 (2) A law enforcement agency may use an automated license plate recognition system or
8 captured license plate data for the purpose of:
9 (a) Identifying a vehicle that was used to facilitate the commission of a crime or used
10 to avoid apprehension for commission of a crime, if the crime:
11 (A) Constitutes a crime under the laws of this state;
12 (B) If committed in another state or jurisdiction, constitutes a crime that is substantially
13 equivalent to a crime under the laws of this state; or
14 (C) Constitutes a federal crime and the use is not contrary to the public policies set forth
15 in ORS 24.500 or any law of this state restricting the use of public resources for prohibited
16 enforcement activities, including ORS 181A.250, 181A.820 and 181A.826;
17 (b) Identifying a vehicle that was used to facilitate the commission of a violation as de-
18 scribed in ORS 153.008, excluding a traffic violation as defined in ORS 801.557;
19 (c) Identifying a vehicle that is registered to a person for whom there is an outstanding
20 criminal warrant for arrest, if the warrant is:
21 (A) For a crime that constitutes a crime under the laws of this state;
22 (B) For a crime that, if committed in another state or jurisdiction, constitutes a crime
23 that is substantially equivalent to a crime under the laws of this state; or
24 (C) A federal judicial warrant for arrest and the use is not contrary to the public policies
25 set forth in ORS 24.500 or any law of this state restricting the use of public resources for
26 prohibited enforcement activities, including ORS 181A.250, 181A.820 and 181A.826;
27 (d) Identifying a vehicle that is associated with a missing or endangered person, including
28 a person who is the subject of an Amber Alert or Silver Alert;
29 (e) Identifying an uninsured vehicle, as that term is defined in ORS 742.504;
30 (f) Identifying a vehicle that is not registered as required under the Oregon Vehicle Code;
31 (g) Regulating the use of parking facilities; or
32 (h) Controlling access to secured areas.
33 (3)(a) For captured license plate data not related to a court proceeding or ongoing crim-
34 inal investigation, the captured license plate data may be retained for no more than 30 days
35 after the captured license plate data is collected.
36 (b) For captured license plate data related to a court proceeding or ongoing criminal in-
37 vestigation, the captured license plate data may be retained for the same period of time that
38 evidence is retained in the normal course of the court’s business.
39 (c) Paragraphs (a) and (b) of this subsection do not apply to the audit information de-
40 scribed in section 6 of this 2026 Act.
41 (4)(a) A law enforcement agency may compare captured license plate data with informa-
42 tion contained in:
43 (A) Records held by the Department of Transportation;
44 (B) The databases of the National Crime Information Center maintained by the Federal
45 Bureau of Investigation;
[4]

