1 (C) The Law Enforcement Data System maintained by the Department of State Police
2 or an equivalent system maintained by another state;
3 (D) The records of the Federal Bureau of Investigation related to kidnappings and miss-
4 ing persons;
5 (E) The missing children and adults clearinghouse established under ORS 181A.300; or
6 (F) Hot lists created or maintained by the law enforcement agency using the automated
7 license plate recognition system or equivalent databases created or maintained by an agency
8 of another state that enforces criminal laws.
9 (b) A law enforcement agency may compare captured license plate data only with infor-
10 mation contained in a system, hot list or database described in paragraph (a)(C) or (F) of this
11 subsection if the system, hot list or database is updated frequently enough to ensure the
12 information contained therein is accurate, relevant, timely and complete.
13 (c) A law enforcement officer or other employee of a law enforcement agency who adds
14 a license plate number, vehicle description or other entry to a hot list must include in the
15 entry:
16 (A) The specific law enforcement purpose for the entry;
17 (B) The name of the officer or other employee who adds the entry; and
18 (C) If the officer or other employee adds the entry on behalf of another employee of the
19 law enforcement agency, the name of that other employee.
20 (5) A law enforcement officer or other employee of a law enforcement agency who
21 searches captured license plate data collected by an automated license plate recognition
22 system under this section shall include the following information in the search entry log for
23 the automated license plate recognition system:
24 (a) The authorized user identifier of the person who conducts the search;
25 (b) The law enforcement agency that employs the person who conducts the search;
26 (c) The search inputs used;
27 (d) The date and time of the search;
28 (e) Any applicable case or reference number;
29 (f) The law enforcement purpose for the search; and
30 (g) If the search is related to an investigation of a crime or violation, the specific type
31 of crime or violation being investigated.
32 (6) Before a law enforcement officer conducts a traffic stop of a driver of a motor vehicle
33 based on an alert, the law enforcement officer or other authorized user shall visually confirm
34 that the vehicle’s license plate number, issuing state and other vehicle characteristics match
35 the alert and that the traffic stop complies with agency policy and applicable law.
36 (7) A law enforcement agency may request access to captured license plate data collected
37 by a private person or entity or non-law enforcement agency, provided that the law
38 enforcement agency accesses or otherwise uses the data for a law enforcement purpose.
39 SECTION 5. Data sharing limitations for law enforcement agencies. (1) A law enforce-
40 ment agency may allow queries of the agency’s captured license plate data by another law
41 enforcement agency.
42 (2)(a) Except as provided in paragraph (b) of this subsection, a law enforcement agency
43 may not provide access to captured license plate data to any government entity or agency
44 not created pursuant to the Oregon Constitution, or the laws or regulations of this state.
45 (b) A law enforcement agency may provide captured license plate data to a government
