13 SECTION 7. Law enforcement agency policies and procedures regarding ALPR systems;
14 requirements. (1) Before deploying or using an automated license plate recognition system
15 or captured license plate data, a law enforcement agency shall establish and publish policies
16 and procedures for the use of an automated license plate recognition system and the use,
17 storage and retention of captured license plate data in accordance with sections 3 to 9 of this
18 2026 Act.
19 (2) The policies and procedures described in subsection (1) of this section must include:
20 (a) Requirements to ensure the security of the automated license plate recognition sys-
21 tem and resulting captured license plate data, including rules governing access to the system
22 and data;
23 (b) Requirements to ensure that information contained in any hot list created or main-
24 tained by the law enforcement agency is accurate, relevant, timely and complete;
25 (c) Training requirements for any authorized users regarding the deployment, use and
26 security of the automated license plate recognition system and captured license plate data;
27 (d) Requirements for the retention and destruction of captured license plate data;
28 (e) A requirement that any contract with a third party vendor for an automated license
29 plate recognition system or related services must include terms providing that:
30 (A) Captured license plate data collected by the automated license plate recognition sys-
31 tem is the property of the law enforcement agency, is not owned by the vendor and may not
32 be used by or licensed to the vendor for any purpose inconsistent with the policies and pro-
33 cedures of the law enforcement agency or the provisions of sections 3 to 9 of this 2026 Act;
34 (B) Any request received by the vendor for access to captured license plate data collected
35 by the automated license plate recognition system, including through a judicial warrant, ju-
36 dicial subpoena or administrative subpoena, must be directed exclusively to the law enforce-
37 ment agency that owns the captured license plate data;
38 (C) Captured license plate data must be encrypted using, at a minimum, end-to-end en-
39 cryption;
40 (D) The vendor must be in compliance with the most current version of the Federal Bu-
41 reau of Investigation Criminal Justice Information Services Security Policy, including, as
42 applicable, execution of the Federal Bureau of Investigation Criminal Justice Information
43 Services Security Addendum, audit rights and prompt notification of security incidents; and
44 (E) The vendor may be held liable for the vendor’s misuse or improper release of cap-
45 tured license plate data collected by the automated license plate recognition system, includ-
[7]

A-Eng. SB 1516
1 ing damages for the misuse or improper release;
2 (f) Requirements for audit processes under section 6 of this 2026 Act; and
3 (g) A prohibition on the use of any captured license plate data collected by the automated
4 license plate recognition system for any purpose not in accordance with sections 3 to 9 of
5 this 2026 Act.
6 SECTION 8. Exception for existing ALPR contracts. (1) Notwithstanding section 7 of this
7 2026 Act, if a law enforcement agency has deployed or is using an automated license plate
8 recognition system on or after the effective date of this 2026 Act pursuant to a contract with
9 a third party vendor for an automated license plate recognition system or related services
10 that was entered into prior to the effective date of this 2026 Act, the law enforcement agency
11 may use the automated license plate recognition system in accordance with the terms of the
12 existing contract for the duration of the contract. The law enforcement agency may not ex-
13 tend or renew the contract or enter into a new contract with a third party vendor for an
14 automated license plate recognition system unless the law enforcement agency and any ex-
15 tended, renewed or new contract will be in compliance with the requirements of sections 3
16 to 9 of this 2026 Act on and after the date on which the contract is extended, renewed or
17 entered into.
18 (2) Notwithstanding subsection (1) of this section, a law enforcement agency that uses
19 an automated license plate recognition system on or after the effective date of this 2026 Act
20 shall comply with the provisions of section 4 of this 2026 Act regardless of the date on which
21 the agency enters, renews or extends a contract with a third party vendor for an automated
22 license plate recognition system or related services.
23 SECTION 9. Action for improper access or disclosure of captured license plate data; ex-
24 ceptions; attorney fees. (1)(a) A vendor that contracts with a law enforcement agency to
25 provide an automated license plate recognition system or related services may not access,
26 disclose, sell, share or otherwise use captured license plate data collected by the automated
27 license plate recognition system.
28 (b) It is not a violation of paragraph (a) of this subsection for a vendor to:
29 (A) Access captured license plate data collected by an automated license plate recognition
30 system for the limited duration and purpose of providing technical support to the law
31 enforcement agency for the system or data if the agency grants express consent for that
32 duration and purpose; or
33 (B) Provide the audit information described under section 6 of this 2026 Act to a law
34 enforcement agency.
35 (2) If a vendor intentionally or with gross negligence accesses, discloses, sells, shares or
36 otherwise uses captured license plate data related to an individual in violation of subsection
37 (1)(a) of this section, the individual may bring a civil action against the vendor for economic
38 and noneconomic damages and equitable relief. If a court awards damages or equitable relief
39 to the individual, the court may award reasonable attorney fees to the individual.
40 (3) Any person may bring a civil action against a vendor that violates subsection (1)(a)
41 of this section to enjoin the violation.
42 (4) The causes of action provided in this section are the exclusive remedies in law or
43 equity for violation of subsection (1)(a) of this section.
