14 JUSTICE REINVESTMENT EQUITY PROGRAM
15
16 SECTION 12. Section 15, chapter 78, Oregon Laws 2022, is amended to read:
17 Sec. 15. (1) The Oregon Criminal Justice Commission shall distribute [the] any moneys [received
18 pursuant to section 14 of this 2022 Act to the Northwest Health Foundation Fund II to fund] appro-
19 priated to the commission for the Justice Reinvestment Equity Program as described in this
20 section. The program shall consist of the provision of subgrants and technical assistance [by the
21 Northwest Health Foundation Fund II], by an intermediary technical assistance provider, to
22 culturally specific organizations and culturally responsive service providers for the following pur-
23 poses:
24 (a) Mental health and substance use disorder treatment;
25 (b) Maternal health services;
26 (c) Trauma-informed restorative justice services;
27 (d) Violence reduction programs, including but not limited to violence interruption mentors or
28 after-school programs focused on art, music, theater or dance;
29 (e) Crisis intervention without police involvement;
30 (f) Reentry programs that are connected to education, workforce development and transitional
31 supports;
32 (g) Long-term supportive housing;
33 (h) Support for setting aside conviction records;
34 (i) Pretrial release support;
35 (j) Services for victims, including incarcerated victims or victims on pretrial release;
36 (k) Programs for persons, and families of persons, who are currently or were formerly
37 incarcerated;
38 (L) Programs designed to reduce recidivism and reduce contact with the criminal justice system;
39 (m) Programs for persons who have been impacted by police violence, either directly or through
40 a family member; or
41 (n) Planning [grants] subgrants and technical assistance to support the development of new
42 culturally specific services, or to strengthen existing services, that are aligned with the other pur-
43 poses described in this subsection.
44 (2) Recognizing that systemic racism exists within this state and within the criminal justice
45 system, and that culturally specific organizations and culturally responsive services must be ex-
[16]

A-Eng. SB 1516
1 panded to address those disparities, the purpose of the Justice Reinvestment Equity Program is to
2 promote racial equity, reduce racial disparities, reduce recidivism and decrease a county’s utiliza-
3 tion of imprisonment in a Department of Corrections institution, all while protecting public safety
4 and holding offenders accountable.
5 (3)(a) As part of the program, the commission shall select a culturally responsive tech-
6 nical assistance provider that has experience working with prior Justice Reinvestment Eq-
7 uity Program subgrantees to serve as an intermediary between the commission and program
8 subgrantees. The commission shall distribute to the technical assistance provider, as a grant,
9 the moneys appropriated to the commission for the program.
10 (b) The technical assistance provider shall develop selection criteria and recommen-
11 dations for subgrants provided as part of the program. The commission has approval au-
12 thority for final subgrant awards based on the selection criteria and recommendations.
13 (c) In consultation with the commission, the technical assistance provider is responsible
14 for:
15 (A) Oversight and compilation of fiscal and data reporting that incorporate measures of
16 success as defined by the technical assistance provider;
17 (B) Administering the application and subgrant management processes for program
18 funding and making recommendations to the commission on final subgrant awards;
19 (C) Assisting subgrantees with the effective implementation and management of program
20 subgrant funds;
21 (D) Organizational capacity-building, with a focus on effective subgrant management and
22 performance of subgrant deliverables; and
23 (E) Developing working relationships between program subgrantees and other organiza-
24 tions funded by the commission to the benefit of individuals and the community.
25 [(3)] (4) Notwithstanding subsection (1) of this section, up to three percent of funds distributed
26 under this section may be used by the [Northwest Health Foundation Fund II] technical assistance
27 provider selected by the commission under subsection (3) of this section for administrative
28 costs.
29 [(4)] (5) The Oregon Criminal Justice Commission may adopt rules to carry out the provisions
30 of this section.
31 [(5)] (6) As used in this section:
32 (a) “Administrative costs” means all costs incurred throughout the administration of the Justice
33 Reinvestment Equity Program that are not directly related to the delivery of program services or
34 projects.
35 (b) “Culturally responsive service” means a service that is respectful of, and relevant to, the
36 beliefs, practices, cultures and linguistic needs of diverse consumer or client populations and com-
37 munities whose members identify as having particular cultural or linguistic affiliations by virtue of
38 their place of birth, ancestry or ethnic origin, religion, preferred language or language spoken at
39 home. A culturally responsive service has the capacity to respond to the issues of diverse commu-
40 nities and require knowledge and capacity at systemic, organizational, professional and individual
41 levels of intervention.
42 (c) “Culturally specific organization” means an organization, or a program within an organiza-
43 tion, that serves a particular cultural community, that is primarily staffed and led by members of
44 that community and that demonstrates self-advocacy, positive cultural identity and intimate knowl-
45 edge of the lived experience of the community, including but not limited to:
[17]

A-Eng. SB 1516
1 (A) The impact of structural and individual racism or discrimination on the community;
2 (B) Specific disparities in access to services and resources experienced by the community; and
3 (C) Community strengths, cultural practices, beliefs and traditions.
4
5 CAPTIONS
6
7 SECTION 13. The unit and section captions used in this 2026 Act are provided only for
8 the convenience of the reader and do not become part of the statutory law of this state or
9 express any legislative intent in the enactment of this 2026 Act.
10
11 EMERGENCY CLAUSE
12
13 SECTION 14. This 2026 Act being necessary for the immediate preservation of the public
14 peace, health and safety, an emergency is declared to exist, and this 2026 Act takes effect
15 on its passage.
